 captures Galápagos animals in action as they feed, play, fight, court, mate, build nests, give birth, raise their young, and cooperate and clash with other species.Watch male Marine Iguanas fight over territory and females; see frigatebirds steal food and nesting materials from other birds; witness the courtship dance of a pair of Blue-footed Boobies; go underwater to glimpse a Galápagos Sea Lion pup playing with its mother; and observe a baby Pacific Green Turtle enter the water for the first time. These and dozens of other unforgettable scenes are all vividly captured here—including many moments that even experienced Galápagos observers may never be lucky enough to see in person.Complete with a brief text that provides essential context, this book will be cherished by Galápagos visitors and anyone else who wants to see incredible animals on the move.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAnimal behaviorzGalapagos IslandsvPictorial works. 0aAnimalszGalapagos IslandsvPictorial works. 0aCoastal animalszGalapagos IslandsvPictorial works. 7aNATURE / Reference.2bisacsh  aAdaptive radiation.  aBaltra Island.  aBiology.  aBlue-footed booby.  aBooby.  aBrown pelican.  aCarapace.  aChristiansen.  aCoast.  aCourtship.  aDaphne Major.  aEcological relationship.  aFauna.  aFernandina Island.  aFlightless cormorant.  aFloreana Island.  aFloreana mockingbird.  aFur seal.  aGiant tortoise.  aGrazing.  aGreen algae.  aInsect.  aLava heron.  aMammal.  aMarine biology.  aMarine iguana.  aMating.  aMedium ground finch.  aMockingbird.  aNomenclature.  aObligate.  aPacific Ocean.  aPredation.  aSantiago Island (Galápagos).  aSardine.  aScientist.  aSeawater.  aSiblicide.  aSouth America.  aSouthern Water.  aStriated heron.  aThe Voyage of the Beagle